web_results.snippet: The jalapeño is a medium-sized chili pepper pod type cultivar of the species Capsicum annuum. A mature jalapeño chili is 5–10 cm long and 25–38 mm wide, and hangs down from the plant. The pungency of jalapeño peppers varies, but is usually between 4,000 and 8,500 units on the Scoville scale.

related_questions.question: Why are jalapeños good for you?
related_questions.snippet: In particular, jalapeños are dense in vitamin A. According to the NIH, vitamin A is vital for vision health, the functioning of the immune system, reproductive health, growth and development, and the functioning of the heart, lungs, and other organs. Jalapeños are also a good source of potassium, vitamin C and folate.
related_questions.title: Are jalapeños good for you? - USA Today

related_questions.question: Are jalapeños good for your stomach?
related_questions.snippet: Yes, jalapeños can benefit gut health. They contain dietary fiber, which supports digestion and bowel regularity. Capsaicin may also have antimicrobial properties that could help maintain a healthy gut microbiome.
related_questions.title: Jalapeno: Health Benefits, Nutrition, Recipes And Side Effects - Netmeds

related_questions.question: What color jalapeño is hottest?
related_questions.snippet: So red jalapeños are older than green jalapeños. The red ones can be pretty hot, especially if they have a lot of striations, but they are also sweeter than the green. If you are trying to avoid the hottest jalapeños (say for a stuffed jalapeno dish), pick the chiles without any striations.

related_questions.question: Is a jalapeño hotter than habanero?
related_questions.snippet: The most notable difference between habanero and jalapeno peppers is their heat level. Habaneros are considerably hotter than jalapenos. On the Scoville Heat Scale, jalapenos typically range from 2,500 to 8,000 Scoville Heat Units (SHU), while habaneros can range from 100,000 to 350,000 SHU or even higher.
